# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: linear-circuit
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:linear-circuit/active-filter] An **active filter** is a type of analog circuit implementing an electronic filter using active components, typically an amplifier.
[src:linear-circuit/active-filter] Amplifiers included in a filter design can be used to improve the cost, performance and predictability of a filter.
[src:linear-circuit/active-filter] An amplifier prevents the load impedance of the following stage from affecting the characteristics of the filter.
[src:linear-circuit/active-filter] An active filter can have complex poles and zeros without using a bulky or expensive inductor.
[src:linear-circuit/active-filter] The shape of the response, the Q (quality factor), and the tuned frequency can often be set with inexpensive variable resistors.
[src:linear-circuit/active-filter] In some active filter circuits, one parameter can be adjusted without affecting the others.
[src:linear-circuit/active-filter] Using active elements has some limitations.
[src:linear-circuit/active-filter] Basic filter design equations neglect the finite bandwidth of amplifiers.
[src:linear-circuit/active-filter] Available active devices have limited bandwidth, so they are often impractical at high frequencies.
[src:linear-circuit/active-filter] Amplifiers consume power and inject noise into a system.
[src:linear-circuit/active-filter] Certain circuit topologies may be impractical if no DC path is provided for bias current to the amplifier elements.
[src:linear-circuit/active-filter] Power handling capability is limited by the amplifier stages.
[src:linear-circuit/active-filter] Active filters can implement the same transfer functions as passive filters.
[src:linear-circuit/active-filter] where most of the offending rumble comes from a particular frequency).
[src:linear-circuit/active-filter] An active filter can have gain, increasing the power available in a signal compared to the input.
[src:linear-circuit/active-filter] Passive filters dissipate energy from a signal and cannot have a net power gain.
[src:linear-circuit/active-filter] This advantage may not be as important for active filters entirely integrated on a chip because the available capacitors have relatively low values and so require high value resistors which take up area of the integrated circuit.
[src:linear-circuit/active-filter] Active filters have good isolation between stages, and can provide high input impedance and low output impedance; this makes their characteristics independent of the source and load impedances.
[src:linear-circuit/active-filter] Multiple stages can be cascaded when desired to improve characteristics.
[src:linear-circuit/active-filter] In contrast, design of multiple-stage passive filters must take into account each stage's frequency-dependent loading of the preceding stage.
[src:linear-circuit/active-filter] It is feasible to make active filters tunable over a wide range, compared with passive filters.
[src:linear-circuit/active-filter] Since inductors are not used, filters can be made in a very compact size and do not produce or interact with magnetic fields that may be present.
[src:linear-circuit/active-filter] Compared with active filters, passive filters require no additional power supplies.
[src:linear-circuit/active-filter] The amplifying devices of an active filter must provide predictable gain and performance over the entire frequency range to be processed; the gain–bandwidth product of the amplifier will constrain the maximum frequency that can be used.
[src:linear-circuit/additive-function] An additive function *f*(*n*) is said to be **completely additive** if $f(ab)=f(a)+f(b)$ holds *for all* positive integers *a* and *b*, even when they are not coprime.
[src:linear-circuit/additive-function] **Totally additive** is also used in this sense by analogy with totally multiplicative functions.
[src:linear-circuit/additive-function] Every completely additive function is additive, but not vice versa.
[src:linear-circuit/additive-function] More generally, we could consider the function $g(n)=c^{f(n)}$ , where c is a nonzero real constant.
[src:linear-circuit/additive-function] Given an additive function f , let its summatory function be defined by ${\textstyle {\mathcal {M}}_{f}(x):=\sum _{n\leq x}f(n)}$ .
[src:linear-circuit/amplifier] An **amplifier**, **electronic amplifier** or (informally) **amp** is an electronic device that can increase the magnitude of a signal (a time-varying voltage or current).
[src:linear-circuit/amplifier] It is a two-port electronic circuit that uses electric power from a power supply to increase the amplitude (magnitude of the voltage or current) of a signal applied to its input terminals, producing a proportionally greater amplitude signal at its output.
[src:linear-circuit/amplifier] The amount of amplification provided by an amplifier is measured by its gain: the ratio of output voltage, current, or power to input.
[src:linear-circuit/amplifier] An amplifier is defined as a circuit that has a power gain greater than one.
[src:linear-circuit/amplifier] An amplifier can be either a separate piece of equipment or an electrical circuit contained within another device.
[src:linear-circuit/amplifier] Amplification is fundamental to modern electronics, and amplifiers are widely used in almost all electronic equipment.
[src:linear-circuit/amplifier] Amplifiers can be categorized in different ways.
[src:linear-circuit/amplifier] One is by the frequency of the electronic signal being amplified.
[src:linear-circuit/amplifier] For example, audio amplifiers amplify signals of less than 20 kHz, radio frequency (RF) amplifiers amplify frequencies in the range between 20 kHz and 300 GHz, and servo amplifiers and instrumentation amplifiers may work with very low frequencies down to direct current.
[src:linear-circuit/amplifier] Amplifiers can also be categorized by their physical placement in the signal chain; a preamplifier may precede other signal processing stages, for example, while a power amplifier is usually used after other amplifier stages to provide enough output power for the final use of the signal.
[src:linear-circuit/amplifier] The first practical electrical device which could amplify was the triode vacuum tube, invented in 1906 by Lee de Forest, which led to the first amplifiers around 1912.
[src:linear-circuit/amplifier] The first practical prominent device that could amplify was the triode vacuum tube, invented in 1906 by Lee De Forest, which led to the first amplifiers around 1912.
[src:linear-circuit/amplifier] Vacuum tubes were used in almost all amplifiers until the 1960s–1970s when transistors replaced them.
[src:linear-circuit/amplifier] Today, most amplifiers use transistors, but vacuum tubes continue to be used in some applications.
[src:linear-circuit/amplifier] The development of audio communication technology in form of the telephone, first patented in 1876, created the need to increase the amplitude of electrical signals to extend the transmission of signals over increasingly long distances.
[src:linear-circuit/amplifier] In telegraphy, this problem had been solved with intermediate devices at stations that replenished the dissipated energy by operating a signal recorder and transmitter back-to-back, forming a relay, so that a local energy source at each intermediate station powered the next leg of transmission.
[src:linear-circuit/amplifier] For duplex transmission, i.e. sending and receiving in both directions, bi-directional relay repeaters were developed starting with the work of C.
[src:linear-circuit/amplifier] Duplex transmission was essential for telephony and the problem was not satisfactorily solved until 1904, when H.
[src:linear-circuit/amplifier] Shreeve of the American Telephone and Telegraph Company improved existing attempts at constructing a telephone repeater consisting of back-to-back carbon-granule transmitter and electrodynamic receiver pairs.
[src:linear-circuit/amplifier] The Shreeve repeater was first tested on a line between Boston and Amesbury, MA, and more refined devices remained in service for some time.
[src:linear-circuit/amplifier] After the turn of the century it was found that negative resistance mercury lamps could amplify, and were also tried in repeaters, with little success.
[src:linear-circuit/amplifier] The development of thermionic valves which began around 1902, provided an entirely electronic method of amplifying signals.
[src:linear-circuit/amplifier] The first practical version of such devices was the Audion triode, invented in 1906 by Lee De Forest, which led to the first amplifiers around 1912.
[src:linear-circuit/amplifier] Since the only previous device which was widely used to strengthen a signal was the relay used in telegraph systems, the amplifying vacuum tube was first called an *electron relay*.
[src:linear-circuit/amplifier] The terms *amplifier* and *amplification*, derived from the Latin *amplificare*, (*to enlarge or expand*), were first used for this new capability around 1915 when triodes became widespread.
[src:linear-circuit/amplifier] The amplifying vacuum tube revolutionized electrical technology.
[src:linear-circuit/amplifier] It made possible long-distance telephone lines, public address systems, radio broadcasting, talking motion pictures, practical audio recording, radar, television, and the first computers.
[src:linear-circuit/amplifier] For 50 years virtually all consumer electronic devices used vacuum tubes.
[src:linear-circuit/amplifier] Early tube amplifiers often had positive feedback (regeneration), which could increase gain but also make the amplifier unstable and prone to oscillation.
[src:linear-circuit/amplifier] Much of the mathematical theory of amplifiers was developed at Bell Telephone Laboratories during the 1920s to 1940s.
[src:linear-circuit/amplifier] Distortion levels in early amplifiers were high, usually around 5%, until 1934, when Harold Black developed negative feedback; this allowed the distortion levels to be greatly reduced, at the cost of lower gain.
[src:linear-circuit/amplifier] Other advances in the theory of amplification were made by Harry Nyquist and Hendrik Wade Bode.
[src:linear-circuit/amplifier] The vacuum tube was virtually the only amplifying device, other than specialized power devices such as the magnetic amplifier and amplidyne, for 40 years.
[src:linear-circuit/amplifier] Power control circuitry used magnetic amplifiers until the latter half of the twentieth century when power semiconductor devices became more economical, with higher operating speeds.
[src:linear-circuit/amplifier] The old Shreeve electroacoustic carbon repeaters were used in adjustable amplifiers in telephone subscriber sets for the hearing impaired until the transistor provided smaller and higher quality amplifiers in the 1950s.
[src:linear-circuit/amplifier] The first working transistor was a point-contact transistor invented by John Bardeen and Walter Brattain in 1947 at Bell Labs, where William Shockley later invented the bipolar junction transistor (BJT) in 1948.
[src:linear-circuit/amplifier] They were followed by the invention of the metal–oxide–semiconductor field-effect transistor (MOSFET) by Mohamed M.
[src:linear-circuit/amplifier] Atalla and Dawon Kahng at Bell Labs in 1959.
[src:linear-circuit/amplifier] Due to MOSFET scaling, the ability to scale down to increasingly small sizes, the MOSFET has since become the most widely used amplifier.
[src:linear-circuit/amplifier] The replacement of electron tubes with transistors during the 1960s and 1970s created a revolution in electronics, making possible a large class of portable electronic devices, such as the transistor radio developed in 1954.
[src:linear-circuit/amplifier] Today, use of vacuum tubes is limited to some high power applications, such as radio transmitters, as well as some musical instrument and high-end audiophile amplifiers.
[src:linear-circuit/amplifier] Beginning in the 1970s, more and more transistors were connected on a single chip thereby creating higher scales of integration (such as small-scale, medium-scale and large-scale integration) in integrated circuits.
[src:linear-circuit/amplifier] Many amplifiers commercially available today are based on integrated circuits.
[src:linear-circuit/amplifier] For special purposes, other active elements have been used.
[src:linear-circuit/amplifier] For example, in the early days of the satellite communication, parametric amplifiers were used.
[src:linear-circuit/amplifier] The core circuit was a diode whose capacitance was changed by an RF signal created locally.
[src:linear-circuit/amplifier] Under certain conditions, this RF signal provided energy that was modulated by the extremely weak satellite signal received at the earth station.
[src:linear-circuit/amplifier] Advances in digital electronics since the late 20th century provided new alternatives to the conventional linear-gain amplifiers by using digital switching to vary the pulse-shape of fixed amplitude signals, resulting in devices such as the Class-D amplifier.
[src:linear-circuit/amplifier] In principle, an amplifier is an electrical two-port network that produces a signal at the output port that is a replica of the signal applied to the input port, but increased in magnitude.
[src:linear-circuit/amplifier] The input port can be idealized as either being a voltage input, which takes no current, with the output proportional to the voltage across the port; or a current input, with no voltage across it, in which the output is proportional to the current through the port.
[src:linear-circuit/amplifier] The output port can be idealized as being either a dependent voltage source, with zero source resistance and its output voltage dependent on the input; or a dependent current source, with infinite source resistance and the output current dependent on the input.
[src:linear-circuit/amplifier] Combinations of these choices lead to four types of ideal amplifiers.
[src:linear-circuit/amplifier] In real amplifiers the ideal impedances are not possible to achieve, but these ideal elements can be used to construct equivalent circuits of real amplifiers by adding impedances (resistance, capacitance and inductance) to the input and output.
[src:linear-circuit/amplifier] For any particular circuit, a small-signal analysis is often used to find the actual impedance.
[src:linear-circuit/amplifier] A small-signal AC test current *Ix* is applied to the input or output node, all external sources are set to AC zero, and the corresponding alternating voltage *Vx* across the test current source determines the impedance seen at that node as *R = Vx / Ix*.
[src:linear-circuit/amplifier] Amplifiers designed to attach to a transmission line at input and output, especially RF amplifiers, do not fit into this classification approach.
[src:linear-circuit/amplifier] Rather than dealing with voltage or current individually, they ideally couple with an input or output impedance matched to the transmission line impedance, that is, match *ratios* of voltage to current.
[src:linear-circuit/amplifier] Many real RF amplifiers come close to this ideal.
[src:linear-circuit/amplifier] Although, for a given appropriate source and load impedance, RF amplifiers can be characterized as amplifying voltage or current, they fundamentally are amplifying power.
[src:linear-circuit/amplifier] Amplifiers are described according to the properties of their inputs, their outputs, and how they relate.
[src:linear-circuit/amplifier] All amplifiers have gain, a multiplication factor that relates the magnitude of some property of the output signal to a property of the input signal.
[src:linear-circuit/amplifier] The gain may be specified as the ratio of output voltage to input voltage (voltage gain), output power to input power (power gain), or some combination of current, voltage, and power.
[src:linear-circuit/amplifier] In many cases the property of the output that varies is dependent on the same property of the input, making the gain unitless (though often expressed in decibels (dB)).
[src:linear-circuit/amplifier] Most amplifiers are designed to be linear.
[src:linear-circuit/amplifier] That is, they provide constant gain for any normal input level and output signal.
[src:linear-circuit/amplifier] If an amplifier's gain is not linear, the output signal can become distorted.
[src:linear-circuit/amplifier] There are, however, cases where variable gain is useful.
[src:linear-circuit/amplifier] Certain signal processing applications use exponential gain amplifiers.
[src:linear-circuit/amplifier] Amplifiers are usually designed to function well in a specific application, for example: radio and television transmitters and receivers, high-fidelity ("hi-fi") stereo equipment, microcomputers and other digital equipment, and guitar and other instrument amplifiers.
[src:linear-circuit/amplifier] Every amplifier includes at least one active device, such as a vacuum tube or transistor.
[src:linear-circuit/amplifier] Negative feedback is a technique used in most modern amplifiers to increase bandwidth, reduce distortion, and control gain.
[src:linear-circuit/amplifier] In a negative feedback amplifier part of the output is fed back and added to the input in the opposite phase, subtracting from the input.
[src:linear-circuit/amplifier] The main effect is to reduce the overall gain of the system.
[src:linear-circuit/amplifier] However, any unwanted signals introduced by the amplifier, such as distortion are also fed back.
[src:linear-circuit/amplifier] Since they are not part of the original input, they are added to the input in opposite phase, subtracting them from the input.
[src:linear-circuit/amplifier] In this way, negative feedback also reduces nonlinearity, distortion and other errors introduced by the amplifier.
[src:linear-circuit/amplifier] Large amounts of negative feedback can reduce errors to the point that the response of the amplifier itself becomes almost irrelevant as long as it has a large gain, and the output performance of the system (the "closed loop performance") is defined entirely by the components in the feedback loop.
[src:linear-circuit/amplifier] This technique is used particularly with operational amplifiers (op-amps).
[src:linear-circuit/amplifier] Non-feedback amplifiers can achieve only about 1% distortion for audio-frequency signals.
[src:linear-circuit/amplifier] With negative feedback, distortion can typically be reduced to 0.001%.
[src:linear-circuit/amplifier] Noise, even crossover distortion, can be practically eliminated.
[src:linear-circuit/amplifier] Negative feedback also compensates for changing temperatures, and degrading or nonlinear components in the gain stage, but any change or nonlinearity in the components in the feedback loop will affect the output.
[src:linear-circuit/amplifier] Indeed, the ability of the feedback loop to define the output is used to make active filter circuits.
[src:linear-circuit/amplifier] Another advantage of negative feedback is that it extends the bandwidth of the amplifier.
[src:linear-circuit/amplifier] The concept of feedback is used in operational amplifiers to precisely define gain, bandwidth, and other parameters entirely based on the components in the feedback loop.
[src:linear-circuit/amplifier] Negative feedback can be applied at each stage of an amplifier to stabilize the operating point of active devices against minor changes in power-supply voltage or device characteristics.
[src:linear-circuit/amplifier] Some feedback, positive or negative, is unavoidable and often undesirable—introduced, for example, by parasitic elements, such as inherent capacitance between input and output of devices such as transistors, and capacitive coupling of external wiring.
[src:linear-circuit/amplifier] Excessive frequency-dependent positive feedback can produce parasitic oscillation and turn an amplifier into an oscillator.
[src:linear-circuit/amplifier] All amplifiers include some form of active device: this is the device that does the actual amplification.
[src:linear-circuit/amplifier] The active device can be a vacuum tube, discrete solid state component, such as a single transistor, or part of an integrated circuit, as in an op-amp.
[src:linear-circuit/amplifier] Transistor amplifiers (or solid state amplifiers) are the most common type of amplifier in use today.
[src:linear-circuit/amplifier] A transistor is used as the active element.
[src:linear-circuit/amplifier] The gain of the amplifier is determined by the properties of the transistor itself as well as the circuit it is contained within.
[src:linear-circuit/amplifier] Common active devices in transistor amplifiers include bipolar junction transistors (BJTs) and metal oxide semiconductor field-effect transistors (MOSFETs).
[src:linear-circuit/amplifier] Some common examples are audio amplifiers in a home stereo or public address system, RF high power generation for semiconductor equipment, to RF and microwave applications such as radio transmitters.
[src:linear-circuit/amplifier] Transistor-based amplification can be realized using various configurations: for example a bipolar junction transistor can realize common base, common collector or common emitter amplification; a MOSFET can realize common gate, common source or common drain amplification.
[src:linear-circuit/amplifier] Each configuration has different characteristics.
[src:linear-circuit/amplifier] Vacuum-tube amplifiers (also known as tube amplifiers or valve amplifiers) use a vacuum tube as the active device.
[src:linear-circuit/amplifier] While semiconductor amplifiers have largely displaced valve amplifiers for low-power applications, valve amplifiers can be much more cost effective in high power applications such as radar, countermeasures equipment, and communications equipment.
[src:linear-circuit/amplifier] Many microwave amplifiers are specially designed valve amplifiers, such as the klystron, gyrotron, traveling wave tube, and crossed-field amplifier, and these microwave valves provide much greater single-device power output at microwave frequencies than solid-state devices.
[src:linear-circuit/amplifier] Vacuum tubes remain in use in some high end audio equipment, as well as in musical instrument amplifiers, due to a preference for "tube sound".
[src:linear-circuit/amplifier] Magnetic amplifiers are devices somewhat similar to a transformer where one winding is used to control the saturation of a magnetic core and hence alter the impedance of the other winding.
[src:linear-circuit/amplifier] They have largely fallen out of use due to development in semiconductor amplifiers but are still useful in HVDC control, and in nuclear power control circuitry due to not being affected by radioactivity.
[src:linear-circuit/amplifier] Negative resistances can be used as amplifiers, such as the tunnel diode amplifier.
[src:linear-circuit/amplifier] A power amplifier is an amplifier designed primarily to increase the power available to a load.
[src:linear-circuit/amplifier] In practice, amplifier power gain depends on the source and load impedances, as well as the inherent voltage and current gain.
[src:linear-circuit/amplifier] A radio frequency (RF) amplifier design typically optimizes impedances for power transfer, while audio and instrumentation amplifier designs normally optimize input and output impedance for least loading and highest signal integrity.
[src:linear-circuit/amplifier] In general, the power amplifier is the last 'amplifier' or actual circuit in a signal chain (the output stage) and is the amplifier stage that requires attention to power efficiency.
[src:linear-circuit/amplifier] Audio power amplifiers are typically used to drive loudspeakers.
[src:linear-circuit/amplifier] They will often have two output channels and deliver equal power to each.
[src:linear-circuit/amplifier] An RF power amplifier is found in radio transmitter final stages.
[src:linear-circuit/amplifier] A servo motor controller amplifies a control voltage to adjust the speed of a motor, or the position of a motorized system.
[src:linear-circuit/amplifier] Power amplifier circuits (output stages) are classified as A, B, AB and C for analog designs—and class D and E for switching designs.
[src:linear-circuit/amplifier] The power amplifier classes are based on the proportion of each input cycle (conduction angle) during which an amplifying device passes current.
[src:linear-circuit/amplifier] The image of the conduction angle derives from amplifying a sinusoidal signal.
[src:linear-circuit/amplifier] If the device is always on, the conducting angle is 360°.
[src:linear-circuit/amplifier] If it is on for only half of each cycle, the angle is 180°.
[src:linear-circuit/amplifier] The angle of flow is closely related to the amplifier power efficiency.
[src:linear-circuit/amplifier] An operational amplifier is an amplifier circuit which typically has very high open loop gain and differential inputs.
[src:linear-circuit/amplifier] Op amps have become very widely used as standardized "gain blocks" in circuits due to their versatility; their gain, bandwidth and other characteristics can be controlled by feedback through an external circuit.
[src:linear-circuit/amplifier] Though the term today commonly applies to integrated circuits, the original operational amplifier design used valves, and later designs used discrete transistor circuits.
[src:linear-circuit/amplifier] A fully differential amplifier is similar to the operational amplifier, but also has differential outputs.
[src:linear-circuit/amplifier] These are usually constructed using BJTs or FETs.
[src:linear-circuit/amplifier] These use balanced transmission lines to separate individual single stage amplifiers, the outputs of which are summed by the same transmission line.
[src:linear-circuit/amplifier] The transmission line is a balanced type with the input at one end and on one side only of the balanced transmission line and the output at the opposite end is also the opposite side of the balanced transmission line.
[src:linear-circuit/amplifier] The gain of each stage adds linearly to the output rather than multiplies one on the other as in a cascade configuration.
[src:linear-circuit/amplifier] This allows a higher bandwidth to be achieved than could otherwise be realised even with the same gain stage elements.
[src:linear-circuit/amplifier] These nonlinear amplifiers have much higher efficiencies than linear amps, and are used where the power saving justifies the extra complexity.
[src:linear-circuit/amplifier] Class-D amplifiers are the main example of this type of amplification.
[src:linear-circuit/amplifier] A negative resistance amplifier is a type of regenerative amplifier that can use the feedback between the transistor's source and gate to transform a capacitive impedance on the transistor's source to a negative resistance on its gate.
[src:linear-circuit/amplifier] Compared to other types of amplifiers, a negative resistance amplifier will require only a tiny amount of power to achieve very high gain, maintaining a good noise figure at the same time.
[src:linear-circuit/amplifier] Video amplifiers are designed to process video signals and have varying bandwidths depending on whether the video signal is for SDTV, EDTV, HDTV 720p or 1080i/p etc.
[src:linear-circuit/amplifier] The specification of the bandwidth itself depends on what kind of filter is used—and at which point (−1 dB or −3 dB for example) the bandwidth is measured.
[src:linear-circuit/amplifier] Certain requirements for step response and overshoot are necessary for an acceptable TV image.
[src:linear-circuit/amplifier] Traveling wave tube amplifiers (TWTAs) are used for high power amplification at low microwave frequencies.
[src:linear-circuit/amplifier] They typically can amplify across a broad spectrum of frequencies; however, they are usually not as tunable as klystrons.
[src:linear-circuit/amplifier] Klystrons are specialized linear-beam vacuum-devices, designed to provide high power, widely tunable amplification of millimetre and sub-millimetre waves.
[src:linear-circuit/amplifier] Klystrons are designed for large scale operations and despite having a narrower bandwidth than TWTAs, they have the advantage of coherently amplifying a reference signal so its output may be precisely controlled in amplitude, frequency and phase.
[src:linear-circuit/amplifier] New materials like gallium nitride (GaN) or GaN on silicon or on silicon carbide/SiC are emerging in HEMT transistors and applications where improved efficiency, wide bandwidth, operation roughly from few to few tens of GHz with output power of few watts to few hundred of watts are needed.
[src:linear-circuit/amplifier] Depending on the amplifier specifications and size requirements microwave amplifiers can be realised as monolithically integrated, integrated as modules or based on discrete parts or any combination of those.
[src:linear-circuit/amplifier] The maser is a non-electronic microwave amplifier.
[src:linear-circuit/amplifier] Instrument amplifiers are a range of audio power amplifiers used to increase the sound level of musical instruments, for example guitars, during performances.
[src:linear-circuit/amplifier] An amplifier's tone mainly comes from the order and amount in which it applies EQ and distortion.
[src:linear-circuit/amplifier] These amplifiers are used to amplify the voice of a person with watts, Examples are Megaphones, Microphones, personal amplifiers, etc.
[src:linear-circuit/amplifier] They are used for sporting events, schools, construction, and fire and safety.
[src:linear-circuit/amplifier] One set of classifications for amplifiers is based on which device terminal is common to both the input and the output circuit.
[src:linear-circuit/amplifier] In the case of bipolar junction transistors, the three classes are common emitter, common base, and common collector.
[src:linear-circuit/amplifier] For field-effect transistors, the corresponding configurations are common source, common gate, and common drain; for vacuum tubes, common cathode, common grid, and common plate.
[src:linear-circuit/amplifier] The common emitter (or common source, common cathode, etc.) is most often configured to provide amplification of a voltage applied between base and emitter, and the output signal taken between collector and emitter is inverted, relative to the input.
[src:linear-circuit/amplifier] The common collector arrangement applies the input voltage between base and collector, and to take the output voltage between emitter and collector.
[src:linear-circuit/amplifier] This causes negative feedback, and the output voltage tends to follow the input voltage.
[src:linear-circuit/amplifier] This arrangement is also used as the input presents a high impedance and does not load the signal source, though the voltage amplification is less than one.
[src:linear-circuit/amplifier] The common-collector circuit is, therefore, better known as an emitter follower, source follower, or cathode follower.
[src:linear-circuit/amplifier] An amplifier whose output exhibits no feedback to its input side is described as 'unilateral'.
[src:linear-circuit/amplifier] The input impedance of a unilateral amplifier is independent of load, and output impedance is independent of signal source impedance.
[src:linear-circuit/amplifier] An amplifier that uses feedback to connect part of the output back to the input is a *bilateral* amplifier.
[src:linear-circuit/amplifier] Bilateral amplifier input impedance depends on the load, and output impedance on the signal source impedance.
[src:linear-circuit/amplifier] All amplifiers are bilateral to some degree; however they may often be modeled as unilateral under operating conditions where feedback is small enough to neglect for most purposes, simplifying analysis (see the common base article for an example).
[src:linear-circuit/amplifier] Another way to classify amplifiers is by the phase relationship of the input signal to the output signal.
[src:linear-circuit/amplifier] An 'inverting' amplifier produces an output 180 degrees out of phase with the input signal (that is, a polarity inversion or mirror image of the input as seen on an oscilloscope).
[src:linear-circuit/amplifier] A 'non-inverting' amplifier maintains the phase of the input signal waveforms.
[src:linear-circuit/amplifier] An emitter follower is a type of non-inverting amplifier, indicating that the signal at the emitter of a transistor is following (that is, matching with unity gain but perhaps an offset) the input signal.
[src:linear-circuit/amplifier] Voltage follower is also non-inverting type of amplifier having unity gain.
[src:linear-circuit/amplifier] This description can apply to a single stage of an amplifier, or to a complete amplifier system.
[src:linear-circuit/amplifier] Other amplifiers may be classified by their function or output characteristics.
[src:linear-circuit/amplifier] These functional descriptions usually apply to complete amplifier systems or sub-systems and rarely to individual stages.
[src:linear-circuit/amplifier] Amplifiers are sometimes classified by the coupling method of the signal at the input, output, or between stages.
[src:linear-circuit/amplifier] By design these amplifiers cannot amplify DC signals as the capacitors block the DC component of the input signal.
[src:linear-circuit/amplifier] RC-coupled amplifiers were used very often in circuits with vacuum tubes or discrete transistors.
[src:linear-circuit/amplifier] In the days of the integrated circuit a few more transistors on a chip are much cheaper and smaller than a capacitor.
[src:linear-circuit/amplifier] This kind of amplifier is most often used in selective radio-frequency circuits.
[src:linear-circuit/amplifier] Quite often LC-coupled and transformer-coupled amplifiers cannot be distinguished as a transformer is some kind of inductor.
[src:linear-circuit/amplifier] This class of amplifier was very uncommon in the vacuum tube days when the anode (output) voltage was at greater than several hundred volts and the grid (input) voltage at a few volts minus.
[src:linear-circuit/amplifier] So they were used only if the gain was specified down to DC (e.g., in an oscilloscope).
[src:linear-circuit/amplifier] In the context of modern electronics developers are encouraged to use directly coupled amplifiers whenever possible.
[src:linear-circuit/amplifier] In FET and CMOS technologies direct coupling is dominant since gates of MOSFETs theoretically pass no current through themselves.
[src:linear-circuit/amplifier] Therefore, DC component of the input signals is automatically filtered.
[src:linear-circuit/amplifier] Depending on the frequency range and other properties amplifiers are designed according to different principles.
[src:linear-circuit/amplifier] Amplifiers that operate down to DC are used only when direct-current response is needed.
[src:linear-circuit/amplifier] Amplifiers for direct current signals are vulnerable to minor variations in the properties of components with time.
[src:linear-circuit/amplifier] Special methods, such as chopper stabilized amplifiers are used to prevent objectionable drift in the amplifier's properties for DC.
[src:linear-circuit/amplifier] "DC-blocking" capacitors can be added to remove DC and sub-sonic frequencies from audio amplifiers.
[src:linear-circuit/amplifier] Amplifiers are designed according to different principles depending on their frequency range and other properties.
[src:linear-circuit/amplifier] As soon as any connection within the circuit gets longer than perhaps 1% of the wavelength of the highest specified frequency (e.g., at 100 MHz the wavelength is 3 m, so the critical connection length is approx.
[src:linear-circuit/amplifier] 3 cm) design properties radically change.
[src:linear-circuit/amplifier] For example, a specified length and width of a PCB trace can be used as a selective or impedance-matching entity.
[src:linear-circuit/amplifier] Above a few hundred MHz, it gets difficult to use discrete elements, especially inductors.
[src:linear-circuit/amplifier] In most cases, PCB traces of very closely defined shapes are used instead (stripline techniques).
[src:linear-circuit/amplifier] The practical amplifier circuit shown above could be the basis for a moderate-power audio amplifier.
[src:linear-circuit/amplifier] It features a typical (though substantially simplified) design as found in modern amplifiers, with a class-AB push–pull output stage, and uses some overall negative feedback.
[src:linear-circuit/amplifier] Bipolar transistors are shown, but this design would also be realizable with FETs or valves.
[src:linear-circuit/amplifier] The input signal is coupled through capacitor C1 to the base of transistor Q1.
[src:linear-circuit/amplifier] The capacitor allows the AC signal to pass, but blocks the DC bias voltage established by resistors R1 and R2 so that any preceding circuit is not affected by it.
[src:linear-circuit/amplifier] Q1 and Q2 form a differential amplifier (an amplifier that multiplies the difference between two inputs by some constant), in an arrangement known as a long-tailed pair.
[src:linear-circuit/amplifier] This arrangement is used to conveniently allow the use of negative feedback, which is fed from the output to Q2 via R7 and R8.
[src:linear-circuit/amplifier] The negative feedback into the difference amplifier allows the amplifier to compare the input to the actual output.
[src:linear-circuit/amplifier] The amplified signal from Q1 is directly fed to the second stage, Q3, which is a common emitter stage that provides further amplification of the signal and the DC bias for the output stages, Q4 and Q5.
[src:linear-circuit/amplifier] R6 provides the load for Q3 (a better design would probably use some form of active load here, such as a constant-current sink).
[src:linear-circuit/amplifier] So far, all of the amplifier is operating in class A.
[src:linear-circuit/amplifier] The output pair are arranged in class-AB push–pull, also called a complementary pair.
[src:linear-circuit/amplifier] They provide the majority of the current amplification (while consuming low quiescent current) and directly drive the load, connected via DC-blocking capacitor C2.
[src:linear-circuit/amplifier] The diodes D1 and D2 provide a small amount of constant voltage bias for the output pair, just biasing them into the conducting state so that crossover distortion is minimized.
[src:linear-circuit/amplifier] That is, the diodes push the output stage firmly into class-AB mode (assuming that the base-emitter drop of the output transistors is reduced by heat dissipation).
[src:linear-circuit/amplifier] This design is simple, but a good basis for a practical design because it automatically stabilises its operating point, since feedback internally operates from DC up through the audio range and beyond.
[src:linear-circuit/amplifier] Further circuit elements would probably be found in a real design that would roll-off the frequency response above the needed range to prevent the possibility of unwanted oscillation.
[src:linear-circuit/amplifier] A common solution to help stabilise the output devices is to include some emitter resistors, typically one ohm or so.
[src:linear-circuit/amplifier] Calculating the values of the circuit's resistors and capacitors is done based on the components employed and the intended use of the amp.
[src:linear-circuit/amplifier] Any real amplifier is an imperfect realization of an ideal amplifier.
[src:linear-circuit/amplifier] An important limitation of a real amplifier is that the output it generates is ultimately limited by the power available from the power supply.
[src:linear-circuit/amplifier] An amplifier saturates and clips the output if the input signal becomes too large for the amplifier to reproduce or exceeds operational limits for the device.
[src:linear-circuit/amplifier] The power supply may influence the output, so must be considered in the design.
[src:linear-circuit/amplifier] The power output from an amplifier cannot exceed its input power.
[src:linear-circuit/amplifier] The amplifier circuit has an "open loop" performance.
[src:linear-circuit/amplifier] This is described by various parameters (gain, slew rate, output impedance, distortion, bandwidth, signal-to-noise ratio, etc.).
[src:linear-circuit/amplifier] Many modern amplifiers use negative feedback techniques to hold the gain at the desired value and reduce distortion.
[src:linear-circuit/amplifier] Negative loop feedback has the intended effect of lowering the output impedance and thereby increasing electrical damping of loudspeaker motion at and near the resonance frequency of the speaker.
[src:linear-circuit/amplifier] When assessing rated amplifier power output, it is useful to consider the applied load, the signal type (e.g., speech or music), required power output duration (i.e., short-time or continuous), and required dynamic range (e.g., recorded or live audio).
[src:linear-circuit/amplifier] In high-powered audio applications that require long cables to the load (e.g., cinemas and shopping centres) it may be more efficient to connect to the load at line output voltage, with matching transformers at source and loads.
[src:linear-circuit/amplifier] This avoids long runs of heavy speaker cables.
[src:linear-circuit/amplifier] To prevent instability or overheating requires care to ensure solid state amplifiers are adequately loaded.
[src:linear-circuit/amplifier] Most have a rated minimum load impedance.
[src:linear-circuit/amplifier] All amplifiers generate heat through electrical losses.
[src:linear-circuit/amplifier] The amplifier must dissipate this heat via convection or forced air cooling.
[src:linear-circuit/amplifier] Heat can damage or reduce electronic component service life.
[src:linear-circuit/amplifier] Designers and installers must also consider heating effects on adjacent equipment.
[src:linear-circuit/amplifier] Different power supply types result in many different methods of bias.
[src:linear-circuit/amplifier] Bias is a technique by which active devices are set to operate in a particular region, or by which the DC component of the output signal is set to the midpoint between the maximum voltages available from the power supply.
[src:linear-circuit/amplifier] Most amplifiers use several devices at each stage; they are typically matched in specifications except for polarity.
[src:linear-circuit/amplifier] Matched inverted polarity devices are called complementary pairs.
[src:linear-circuit/amplifier] Class-A amplifiers generally use only one device, unless the power supply is set to provide both positive and negative voltages, in which case a dual device symmetrical design may be used.
[src:linear-circuit/amplifier] Class-C amplifiers, by definition, use a single polarity supply.
[src:linear-circuit/amplifier] Amplifiers often have multiple stages in cascade to increase gain.
[src:linear-circuit/amplifier] Each stage of these designs may be a different type of amp to suit the needs of that stage.
[src:linear-circuit/amplifier] For instance, the first stage might be a class-A stage, feeding a class-AB push–pull second stage, which then drives a class-G final output stage, taking advantage of the strengths of each type, while minimizing their weaknesses.
[src:linear-circuit/analog-multiplier] An **analog multiplier** is an electronic circuit that produces an output level that is the mathematical product of the levels of its two analog signal inputs.
[src:linear-circuit/analog-multiplier] Such circuits may be used to implement related functions such as *squares* by applying the same signal to both inputs, and *square roots*.
[src:linear-circuit/analog-multiplier] Electronic analog multipliers are classified by their function.
[src:linear-circuit/analog-multiplier] A single-quadrant multiplier permits only one, typically positive, level on the inputs.
[src:linear-circuit/analog-multiplier] A two-quadrant multiplier permits one input signal to swing to positive and negative levels, while the second input remains positive.
[src:linear-circuit/analog-multiplier] In a **four-quadrant multiplier** all inputs may swing to positive or negative levels, producing a positive or negative output level.
[src:linear-circuit/analog-multiplier] If one input of an analog multiplier is held at a steady voltage, a signal at the second input is scaled in proportion to the level on the fixed input.
[src:linear-circuit/analog-multiplier] This may be considered a voltage-controlled amplifier or variable-gain amplifier.
[src:linear-circuit/analog-multiplier] Applications are for electronic volume control and automatic gain control (AGC).
[src:linear-circuit/analog-multiplier] Although analog multipliers are often used for such applications, voltage-controlled amplifiers are not necessarily true analog multipliers.
[src:linear-circuit/analog-multiplier] For example, an integrated circuit designed to be used as a volume control may have a signal input designed for 1 Vp-p, and a control input designed for 0-5 V dc; that is, the two inputs are not symmetrical and the control input has a limited bandwidth.
[src:linear-circuit/analog-multiplier] By contrast, in what is generally considered to be a *true* analog multiplier, the two signal inputs have identical characteristics.
[src:linear-circuit/analog-multiplier] Applications specific to a true analog multiplier are those where both inputs are signals, for example in a frequency mixer or an analog circuit to implement a discrete Fourier transform.
[src:linear-circuit/analog-multiplier] Because the precision required for the device to be accurate and linear over the input range, a true analog multiplier is generally a much more expensive part than a voltage-controlled amplifier.
[src:linear-circuit/analog-multiplier] Analog multiplication can be accomplished by using the Hall effect.
[src:linear-circuit/analog-multiplier] The Gilbert cell is a circuit whose output current is a four-quadrant multiplication of its two differential inputs.
[src:linear-circuit/analog-multiplier] Integrated circuits analog multipliers are incorporated into many applications, such as a true RMS converter, but a number of general purpose analog multiplier building blocks are available such as the four-quadrant multiplier.
[src:linear-circuit/analog-multiplier] General-purpose devices usually comprise attenuators or amplifiers on the inputs or outputs in order to allow the signal to be scaled within the voltage limits of the circuit.
[src:linear-circuit/analog-multiplier] Although analog multiplier circuits are very similar to operational amplifiers, they are far more susceptible to noise and offset voltage-related problems as these errors may become multiplied.
[src:linear-circuit/analog-multiplier] When dealing with high-frequency signals, phase-related problems may be quite complex.
[src:linear-circuit/analog-multiplier] This means they have a relatively high cost and so they are generally used only for circuits where they are indispensable.
[src:linear-circuit/analog-multiplier] Some commonly available analog multiplier integrated circuits are the type MPY634 by Texas Instruments, AD534, AD632 and AD734 by Analog Devices, HA-2556 from Intersil, and others.
[src:linear-circuit/analog-multiplier] In most cases, the functions performed by an analog multiplier may be performed better and at lower cost using digital signal processing techniques.
[src:linear-circuit/analog-multiplier] At low frequencies, a digital solution is cheaper and more effective and allows the circuit function to be modified in firmware.
[src:linear-circuit/analog-multiplier] As frequencies rise, the cost of implementing digital solutions increases much more steeply than for analog solutions.
[src:linear-circuit/analog-multiplier] As digital technology advances, the use of analog multipliers tends to be ever more marginalized towards higher-frequency circuits or very specialized applications.
[src:linear-circuit/analog-multiplier] In addition, most *signals* are now destined to become digitized sooner or later in the signal path, and if at all possible the functions that would require a multiplier tend to be moved to the digital side.
[src:linear-circuit/analog-multiplier] For example, in early digital multimeters, true RMS functions were provided by external analog multiplier circuits.
[src:linear-circuit/analog-multiplier] Nowadays (with the exception of high-frequency measurements) the tendency is to increase the sampling rate of the ADC in order to digitize the input signal allowing RMS and a whole range of other functions to be carried out by a digital processor.
[src:linear-circuit/analog-multiplier] However, blindly digitizing the signal as early in the signal path as possible costs unreasonable amounts of power due to the need for high-speed ADCs.
[src:linear-circuit/analog-multiplier] A much more efficient solution involves analog preprocessing to condition the signal and reduce its bandwidth so that energy is spent to digitize only the bandwidth that contains useful information.
[src:linear-circuit/analog-multiplier] In addition, digitally controlled resistors allow microcontrollers to implement many functions such as tone control and AGC without having to process the digitized signal directly.
[src:linear-circuit/analog-signal] An **analog signal** (American English) or **analogue signal** (British and Commonwealth English) is any signal, typically a continuous-time signal, representing some other quantity, i.e., *analogous* to another quantity.
[src:linear-circuit/analog-signal] For example, in an analog audio signal, the instantaneous signal voltage varies in a manner *analogous to* the pressure of the sound waves.
[src:linear-circuit/analog-signal] In contrast, a digital signal represents the original time-varying quantity as a sampled sequence of quantized numeric values, typically but not necessarily in the form of a binary value.
[src:linear-circuit/analog-signal] Digital sampling imposes some bandwidth and dynamic range constraints on the representation and adds quantization noise.
[src:linear-circuit/analog-signal] The term *analog signal* usually refers to electrical signals; however, mechanical, pneumatic, hydraulic, and other systems may also convey or be considered analog signals.
[src:linear-circuit/analog-signal] An analog signal uses some property of the medium to convey the signal's information.
[src:linear-circuit/analog-signal] For example, an aneroid barometer uses rotary position as the signal to convey pressure information.
[src:linear-circuit/analog-signal] In an electrical signal, the voltage, current, or frequency of the signal may be varied to represent the information.
[src:linear-circuit/analog-signal] Any information may be conveyed by an analog signal; such a signal may be a measured response to changes in a physical variable, such as sound, light, temperature, position, or pressure.
[src:linear-circuit/analog-signal] The physical variable is converted to an analog signal by a transducer.
[src:linear-circuit/analog-signal] For example, sound striking the diaphragm of a microphone induces corresponding fluctuations in the current produced by a coil in an electromagnetic microphone or the voltage produced by a condenser microphone.
[src:linear-circuit/analog-signal] The voltage or the current is said to be an *analog* of the sound.
[src:linear-circuit/analog-signal] An analog signal is subject to electronic noise and distortion introduced by communication channels, recording and signal processing operations, which can progressively degrade the signal-to-noise ratio (SNR).
[src:linear-circuit/analog-signal] As the signal is transmitted, copied, or processed, the unavoidable noise introduced in the signal path will accumulate as a generation loss, progressively and irreversibly degrading the SNR, until in extreme cases, the signal can be overwhelmed.
[src:linear-circuit/analog-signal] Noise can show up as hiss and intermodulation distortion in audio signals, or snow in video signals.
[src:linear-circuit/analog-signal] Generation loss is irreversible as there is no reliable method to distinguish the noise from the signal.
[src:linear-circuit/analog-signal] Note that, despite a popular misconception, analog representations do not provide "infinite" resolution or accuracy, due to this inevitable presence of noise (and therefore error) in any real-world system.
[src:linear-circuit/analog-signal] Converting an analog signal to digital form introduces a low-level quantization noise into the signal due to finite resolution of digital systems.
[src:linear-circuit/analog-signal] Once in digital form, the signal can be transmitted, stored, and processed without introducing additional noise or distortion using error detection and correction.
[src:linear-circuit/analog-signal] Noise accumulation in analog systems can be minimized by electromagnetic shielding, balanced lines, low-noise amplifiers and high-quality electrical components.
[src:linear-circuit/analogue-electronics] An analogue signal uses some attribute of the medium to convey the signal's information.
[src:linear-circuit/analogue-electronics] For example, an aneroid barometer uses the angular position of a needle on top of a contracting and expanding box as the signal to convey the information of changes in atmospheric pressure.
[src:linear-circuit/analogue-electronics] Electrical signals may represent information by changing their voltage, current, frequency, or total charge.
[src:linear-circuit/analogue-electronics] Information is converted from some other physical form (such as sound, light, temperature, pressure, position) to an electrical signal by a transducer which converts one type of energy into another (e.g. a microphone).
[src:linear-circuit/analogue-electronics] The signals take any value from a given range, and each unique signal value represents different information.
[src:linear-circuit/analogue-electronics] Any change in the signal is meaningful, and each level of the signal represents a different level of the phenomenon that it represents.
[src:linear-circuit/analogue-electronics] For example, suppose the signal is being used to represent temperature, with one volt representing one degree Celsius.
[src:linear-circuit/analogue-electronics] In such a system, 10 volts would represent 10 degrees, and 10.1 volts would represent 10.1 degrees.
[src:linear-circuit/analogue-electronics] Another method of conveying an analogue signal is to use modulation.
[src:linear-circuit/analogue-electronics] In this, some base carrier signal has one of its properties altered: amplitude modulation (AM) involves altering the amplitude of a sinusoidal voltage waveform by the source information, frequency modulation (FM) changes the frequency.
[src:linear-circuit/analogue-electronics] Other techniques, such as phase modulation or changing the phase of the carrier signal, are also used.
[src:linear-circuit/analogue-electronics] In an analogue sound recording, the variation in pressure of a sound striking a microphone creates a corresponding variation in the current passing through it or voltage across it.
[src:linear-circuit/analogue-electronics] An increase in the volume of the sound causes the fluctuation of the current or voltage to increase proportionally while keeping the same waveform or shape.
[src:linear-circuit/analogue-electronics] Mechanical, pneumatic, hydraulic, and other systems may also use analogue signals.
[src:linear-circuit/analogue-electronics] Analogue systems invariably include noise, random disturbances or variations, some caused by the random thermal vibrations of atomic particles.
[src:linear-circuit/analogue-electronics] Since all variations of an analogue signal are significant, any disturbance is equivalent to a change in the original signal and so appears as noise.
[src:linear-circuit/analogue-electronics] As the signal is copied and re-copied, or transmitted over long distances, these random variations become more significant and lead to signal degradation.
[src:linear-circuit/analogue-electronics] Other sources of noise may include crosstalk from other signals or poorly designed components.
[src:linear-circuit/analogue-electronics] These disturbances may be reduced by use of shielding and low-noise amplifiers.
[src:linear-circuit/analogue-electronics] Since the information is encoded differently in analogue and digital electronics, the way they process a signal is consequently different.
[src:linear-circuit/analogue-electronics] All operations that can be performed on an analogue signal such as amplification, filtering, limiting, and others, can also be duplicated in the digital domain.
[src:linear-circuit/analogue-electronics] Every digital circuit is also an analogue circuit, in that the behaviour of any digital circuit can be explained using the rules of analogue circuits.
[src:linear-circuit/analogue-electronics] The use of microelectronics has made digital devices cheap and widely available.
[src:linear-circuit/analogue-electronics] The effect of noise on an analogue circuit is a function of the level of noise.
[src:linear-circuit/analogue-electronics] The greater the noise level, the more the analogue signal is disturbed, slowly becoming less usable.
[src:linear-circuit/analogue-electronics] Because of this, analogue signals are said to "fail gracefully".
[src:linear-circuit/analogue-electronics] Analogue signals can still contain intelligible information with very high levels of noise.
[src:linear-circuit/analogue-electronics] Digital circuits, on the other hand, are not affected at all by the presence of noise until a certain threshold is reached, at which point they fail catastrophically.
[src:linear-circuit/analogue-electronics] For digital telecommunications, it is possible to increase the noise threshold with the use of error detection and correction coding schemes and algorithms.
[src:linear-circuit/analogue-electronics] Nevertheless, there is still a point at which catastrophic failure of the link occurs.
[src:linear-circuit/analogue-electronics] In digital electronics, because the information is quantized, as long as the signal stays inside a range of values, it represents the same information.
[src:linear-circuit/analogue-electronics] In digital circuits the signal is regenerated at each logic gate, lessening or removing noise.
[src:linear-circuit/analogue-electronics] In analogue circuits, signal loss can be regenerated with amplifiers.
[src:linear-circuit/analogue-electronics] However, noise is cumulative throughout the system and the amplifier itself will add to the noise according to its noise figure.
[src:linear-circuit/analogue-electronics] A number of factors affect how precise a signal is, mainly the noise present in the original signal and the noise added by processing (see signal-to-noise ratio).
[src:linear-circuit/analogue-electronics] Fundamental physical limits such as the shot noise in components limits the resolution of analogue signals.
[src:linear-circuit/analogue-electronics] In digital electronics additional precision is obtained by using additional digits to represent the signal.
[src:linear-circuit/analogue-electronics] The practical limit in the number of digits is determined by the performance of the analogue-to-digital converter (ADC), since digital operations can usually be performed without loss of precision.
[src:linear-circuit/analogue-electronics] The ADC takes an analogue signal and changes it into a series of binary numbers.
[src:linear-circuit/analogue-electronics] The ADC may be used in simple digital display devices, e. g., thermometers or light meters but it may also be used in digital sound recording and in data acquisition.
[src:linear-circuit/analogue-electronics] However, a digital-to-analogue converter (DAC) is used to change a digital signal to an analogue signal.
[src:linear-circuit/analogue-electronics] A DAC takes a series of binary numbers and converts it to an analogue signal.
[src:linear-circuit/analogue-electronics] It is common to find a DAC in the gain-control system of an op-amp which in turn may be used to control digital amplifiers and filters.
[src:linear-circuit/analogue-electronics] Analogue circuits are typically harder to design, requiring more skill than comparable digital systems to conceptualize.
[src:linear-circuit/analogue-electronics] An analogue circuit is usually designed by hand because the application is built into the hardware.
[src:linear-circuit/analogue-electronics] Digital hardware, on the other hand, has a great deal of commonality across applications and can be mass-produced in a standardised form.
[src:linear-circuit/analogue-electronics] Hardware design consists largely of repeated identical blocks and the design process can be highly automated.
[src:linear-circuit/analogue-electronics] This is one of the main reasons that digital systems have become more common than analogue devices.
[src:linear-circuit/analogue-electronics] However, the application of digital hardware is a function of the software/firmware and creating this is still largely a labour-intensive process.
[src:linear-circuit/analogue-electronics] Since the early 2000s, there were some platforms that were developed which enabled analogue design to be defined using software - which allows faster prototyping.
[src:linear-circuit/analogue-electronics] Furthermore, if a digital electronic device is to interact with the real world, it will always need an analogue interface.
[src:linear-circuit/analogue-electronics] For example, every digital radio receiver has an analogue preamplifier as the first stage in the receive chain.
[src:linear-circuit/analogue-electronics] Design of analogue circuits has been greatly eased by the advent of software circuit simulators such as SPICE.
[src:linear-circuit/analogue-electronics] IBM developed their own in-house simulator, ASTAP, in the 1970s which used an unusual (compared to other simulators) sparse matrix method of circuit analysis.
[src:linear-circuit/analogue-electronics] Analogue circuits can be entirely passive, consisting of resistors, capacitors and inductors.
[src:linear-circuit/analogue-electronics] Active circuits also contain active elements such as transistors.
[src:linear-circuit/analogue-electronics] Traditional circuits are built from lumped elements – that is, discrete components.
[src:linear-circuit/analogue-electronics] However, an alternative is distributed-element circuits, built from pieces of transmission line.
[src:linear-circuit/analysis] The word comes from the Ancient Greek ἀνάλυσις (*analysis*, "a breaking-up" or "an untying" from *ana-* "up, throughout" and *lysis* "a loosening").
[src:linear-circuit/analysis] From it also comes the word's plural, *analyses*.
[src:linear-circuit/analysis] As a formal concept, the method has variously been ascribed to René Descartes (*Discourse on the Method*), and Galileo Galilei.
[src:linear-circuit/analysis] It has also been ascribed to Isaac Newton, in the form of a practical method of physical discovery (which he did not name).
[src:linear-circuit/analysis] The converse of analysis is synthesis: putting the pieces back together again in a new or different whole.
[src:linear-circuit/analysis] Academic analysis is a systematic, methodological approach to inquiry used across scholarly disciplines to deconstruct complex ideas, texts, data, or systems.
[src:linear-circuit/analysis] Its primary aim is to foster a deeper, evidence-based understanding, challenge assumptions, and contribute to a body of knowledge through critical examination and rigorous argumentation.
[src:linear-circuit/analysis] This form of analysis is foundational to higher education and research, distinguished by its adherence to disciplinary conventions, peer review, and the use of established theoretical or conceptual frameworks.
[src:linear-circuit/analysis] In the humanities, it often involves hermeneutic or discourse analysis to interpret the meaning, context, and ideology within texts and artifacts.
[src:linear-circuit/analysis] In the social sciences, analysis frequently employs qualitative methods (e.g., thematic analysis, content analysis) and quantitative methods (e.g., statistical analysis, econometrics) to examine human behavior and societal structures.
[src:linear-circuit/analysis] In the natural and formal sciences, the analytical process is characterized by hypothesis testing, mathematical modeling, and the reproducible analysis of empirical data.
[src:linear-circuit/analysis] A cornerstone of academic analysis is reflexivity, where scholars critically examine their own role, potential biases, and the influence of their theoretical position on the analytical process.
[src:linear-circuit/analysis] The product of academic analysis is typically a sustained argument presented in a format such as a monograph, journal article, or dissertation, which is subjected to peer evaluation for validity, originality, and contribution to the field.
[src:linear-circuit/analysis] Linguistics is the scientific study of language.
[src:linear-circuit/analysis] It involves the systematic analysis of the properties of specific languages as well as the universal characteristics of language in general, including its structure, use, and cognitive and social aspects.
[src:linear-circuit/analysis] Linguistics explores individual languages and language in general by breaking language down into component parts for analysis.
[src:linear-circuit/analysis] Theoretical linguistics is concerned with developing a general framework for understanding the fundamental nature of language.
[src:linear-circuit/analysis] Linguistics also encompasses the study of language change over time, known as historical linguistics.
[src:linear-circuit/analysis] Linguistics examines these areas using a range of methods, including tools from computational linguistics that involve computational modelling, statistics, and modeling of natural language.
[src:linear-circuit/analysis] The field takes applied approaches, utilizing scientific findings for practical purposes under the umbrella of applied linguistics.
[src:linear-circuit/analysis] This includes understanding language acquisition and individual language development across the human lifespan, encompassing both first-language acquisition in children and second-language learning in adults.
[src:linear-circuit/analysis] Applied linguistics also addresses clinical issues in communication disorders, applying linguistic theory and methods to their study, diagnosis, and assessment.
[src:linear-circuit/analysis] It also includes improving language education and other applied and interdisciplinary subfields such as computational linguistics, as well as areas such as stylistics.
[src:linear-circuit/analysis] Literary criticism is the analysis of literature.
[src:linear-circuit/analysis] The focus can be as diverse as the analysis of Homer or Freud.
[src:linear-circuit/analysis] While not all literary-critical methods are primarily analytical in nature, the main approach to the teaching of literature in the west since the mid-twentieth century, literary formal analysis or close reading, is.
[src:linear-circuit/analysis] For an example of its use, analysis of the concentration of elements is important in managing a nuclear reactor, so nuclear scientists will analyze neutron activation to develop discrete measurements within vast samples.
[src:linear-circuit/analysis] A matrix can have a considerable effect on the way a chemical analysis is conducted and the quality of its results.
[src:linear-circuit/analysis] Analysis can be done manually or with a device.
[src:linear-circuit/analysis] It is concerned with which components are in a given sample or compound.
[src:linear-circuit/analysis] It is to determine the quantity of individual component present in a given sample or compound.
[src:linear-circuit/analysis] Example: To find concentration by uv-spectrophotometer.
[src:linear-circuit/analysis] Chemists can use isotope analysis to assist analysts with issues in anthropology, archeology, food chemistry, forensics, geology, and a host of other questions of physical science.
[src:linear-circuit/analysis] Analysts can discern the origins of natural and man-made isotopes in the study of environmental radioactivity.
[src:linear-circuit/analysis] Analysts in the field of engineering look at requirements, structures, mechanisms, systems and dimensions.
[src:linear-circuit/analysis] Electrical engineers analyse systems in electronics.
[src:linear-circuit/analysis] Life cycles and system failures are broken down and studied by engineers.
[src:linear-circuit/analysis] It is also looking at different factors incorporated within the design.
[src:linear-circuit/analysis] Modern mathematical analysis is the study of infinite processes.
[src:linear-circuit/analysis] It is the branch of mathematics that includes calculus.
[src:linear-circuit/analysis] It can be applied in the study of classical concepts of mathematics, such as real numbers, complex variables, trigonometric functions, and algorithms, or of non-classical concepts like constructivism, harmonics, infinity, and vectors.
[src:linear-circuit/analysis] In statistics, the term *analysis* may refer to any method used for data analysis.
[src:linear-circuit/analysis] The field of intelligence employs analysts to break down and understand a wide array of questions.
[src:linear-circuit/analysis] Intelligence agencies may use heuristics, inductive and deductive reasoning, social network analysis, dynamic network analysis, link analysis, and brainstorming to sort through problems they face.
[src:linear-circuit/analysis] Military intelligence may explore issues through the use of game theory, Red Teaming, and wargaming.
[src:linear-circuit/analysis] Signals intelligence applies cryptanalysis and frequency analysis to break codes and ciphers.
[src:linear-circuit/analysis] Business intelligence applies theories of competitive intelligence analysis and competitor analysis to resolve questions in the marketplace.
[src:linear-circuit/analysis] Law enforcement intelligence applies a number of theories in crime analysis.
[src:linear-circuit/linear-circuit] A **linear circuit** is an electronic circuit which obeys the superposition principle.
[src:linear-circuit/linear-circuit] It is called a linear circuit because the output voltage and current of such a circuit are linear functions of its input voltage and current.
[src:linear-circuit/linear-circuit] This kind of linearity is not the same as that of straight-line graphs.
[src:linear-circuit/linear-circuit] A linear circuit with constant component values is called *linear time-invariant* (LTI).
[src:linear-circuit/linear-circuit] Informally, a linear circuit is one in which the electronic components' values (such as resistance, capacitance, inductance, gain, etc.) do not change with the level of voltage or current in the circuit.
[src:linear-circuit/linear-circuit] Linear circuits are important because they can amplify and process electronic signals without distortion.
[src:linear-circuit/linear-circuit] An example of an electronic device that uses linear circuits is an amplifier.
[src:linear-circuit/linear-circuit] That is, a linear circuit is a circuit in which (1) the output when a sum of two signals is applied is equal to the sum of the outputs when the two signals are applied separately, and (2) scaling the input signal $x(t)$ by a factor h scales the output signal $F(x(t))$ by the same factor.
[src:linear-circuit/linear-circuit] A linear circuit is one that has no nonlinear electronic components in it.
[src:linear-circuit/linear-circuit] Examples of linear circuits are amplifiers, differentiators, and integrators, linear electronic filters, or any circuit composed exclusively of *ideal* resistors, capacitors, inductors, op-amps (in the "non-saturated" region), and other "linear" circuit elements.
[src:linear-circuit/linear-circuit] Some examples of nonlinear electronic components are: diodes, transistors, and iron core inductors and transformers when the core is saturated.
[src:linear-circuit/linear-circuit] Some examples of circuits that operate in a nonlinear way are mixers, modulators, rectifiers, radio receiver detectors and digital logic circuits.
[src:linear-circuit/linear-circuit] Linear time-invariant circuits are important because they can process analog signals without introducing intermodulation distortion.
[src:linear-circuit/linear-circuit] This means that separate frequencies in the signal stay separate and do not mix, creating new frequencies (heterodynes).
[src:linear-circuit/linear-circuit] They are also easier to understand and analyze.
[src:linear-circuit/linear-circuit] Because they obey the superposition principle, linear circuits are governed by linear differential equations, and can be analyzed with powerful mathematical frequency domain techniques, including Fourier analysis and the Laplace transform.
[src:linear-circuit/linear-circuit] These also give an intuitive understanding of the qualitative behavior of the circuit, characterizing it using terms such as gain, phase shift, resonant frequency, bandwidth, Q factor, poles, and zeros.
[src:linear-circuit/linear-circuit] The analysis of a linear circuit can often be done by hand using a scientific calculator.
[src:linear-circuit/linear-circuit] In contrast, nonlinear circuits usually do not have closed form solutions.
[src:linear-circuit/linear-circuit] They must be analyzed using approximate numerical methods by electronic circuit simulation computer programs such as SPICE, if accurate results are desired.
[src:linear-circuit/linear-circuit] The behavior of such linear circuit elements as resistors, capacitors, and inductors can be specified by a single number (resistance, capacitance, inductance, respectively).
[src:linear-circuit/linear-circuit] In contrast, a nonlinear element's behavior is specified by its detailed transfer function, which may be given by a curved line on a graph.
[src:linear-circuit/linear-circuit] So specifying the characteristics of a nonlinear circuit requires more information than is needed for a linear circuit.
[src:linear-circuit/linear-circuit] "Linear" circuits and systems form a separate category within electronic manufacturing.
[src:linear-circuit/linear-circuit] Manufacturers of transistors and integrated circuits often divide their product lines into 'linear' and 'digital' lines.
[src:linear-circuit/linear-circuit] Nonlinear elements such as transistors tend to behave linearly when small AC signals are applied to them.
[src:linear-circuit/linear-circuit] So in analyzing many circuits where the signal levels are small, for example those in TV and radio receivers, nonlinear elements can be replaced with a linear small-signal model, allowing linear analysis techniques to be used.
[src:linear-circuit/linear-circuit] Conversely, all circuit elements, even "linear" elements, show nonlinearity as the signal level is increased.
[src:linear-circuit/linear-circuit] If nothing else, the power supply voltage to the circuit usually puts a limit on the magnitude of voltage output from a circuit.
[src:linear-circuit/linear-circuit] Above that limit, the output ceases to scale in magnitude with the input, failing the definition of linearity.
